<TD WIDTH=450 VALIGN="TOP"><p><CENTER>
<!-- <IMG SRC="graphics/schottky1.gif" ALT="Schottky" WIDTH=225 HEIGHT=100>-->
<IMG SRC="graphics/schottky2.gif" ALT="Schottky" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=67>
<!-- <IMG SRC="graphics/schottky3.gif" ALT="Schottky" WIDTH=113 HEIGHT=50>-->
</CENTER></TD>
<TD WIDTH=10 ALIGN="LEFT"><BR>
<!-- <FONT  SIZE=+1><B><A HREF="product-info/schottky/sample.htm">FREE Sample Offer</a></B></FONT>--></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=460 COLSPAN=2 VALIGN="TOP">
The five most important characteristics of a Schottky rectifier are (1) forward
voltage drop, (2) reverse leakage current, (3) reverse blocking voltage, (4)
maximum permissible junction temperature, and (5) avalanche energy handling. IR
offers Schottkys made by several different processes, each producing a
different mix of electrical characteristics. The size of the Schottky die in
combination with the package determines the current rating. IR's Schottky
packages range from surface mount and axial lead types with ratings of a few
amps, to large dual Schottky modules with ratings in excess of 400A. Evolving
new power supply requirements and evolving Schottky processes and packages will
continue to add new device types to the range.<p>
</TD>
</TR>
